value.value: absence of the short projection extending from the base of the manubrium of the malleus which contacts the upper part of the tympanic membrane where the tympanic cavity makes a deep pocket (epitympanic pocket) surrounding the cartilaginous nodule

any structural anomaly of a membrane-bounded organelle of eukaryotic cells in which chromosomes are housed and replicated; in most cells, the nucleus contains all of the cell's chromosomes except the organellar chromosomes, and is the site of RNA synthesis and processing, but in some species, or in specialized cell types, RNA metabolism or DNA replication may be absent

increased size of the two small, paired endocrine glands, usually found embedded in the connective tissue capsule on the posterior surface of the thyroid gland; they secrete parathyroid hormone (PTH) that regulates calcium and phosphorous metabolism

decreased size of the two small, paired endocrine glands, usually found embedded in the connective tissue capsule on the posterior surface of the thyroid gland; they secrete parathyroid hormone (PTH) that regulates calcium and phosphorous metabolism

presence of melanocytes and/or melanin in either of the two small, paired endocrine glands, usually found embedded in the connective tissue capsule on the posterior surface of the thyroid gland; they secrete parathyroid hormone (PTH) that regulates calcium and phosphorous metabolism
aberrant differentiation of pulmonary tissues

overproduction and deficient calcification of osteoid tissue due to vitamin D deficiency; can lead to skeletal deformities, growth defects, hypocalcemia, and sometimes tetany; skeletal fractures occur frequently
abnormal formation of the organ system that converts ingested food to nutrients and energy
any structural anomaly of the cartilaginous structures that support the trachea

any anomaly in the process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving macromolecules by a mechanism that is mediated by DNA, is mitotically or meiotically heritable, or is stably self-propagated in the cytoplasm of a resting cell, and does not entail a change in DNA sequence
the establishment of heritable alterations in the activity of a gene that depend on whether it passed through the maternal germline, but that are not encoded by DNA itself
establishment of heritable alterations in the activity of a gene that depend on whether it passed through the paternal germline, but that are not encoded by DNA itself
a urethral opening located below the normal location; in males, the opening is usually on the ventral surface of the penis, and in females, the opening is usually in the vagina

absence of or reduction in the separation of the single opening of the digestive, urinary, and reproductive tracts (cloaca) into multiple isolated openings during development, may result in hypospadia, reduced anogenital distance, or persistent cloaca

any structural anomaly of the external feminine genital organs, collectively known as the vulva and composed of the mons pubis, the labia majora and minora, the clitoris, the vestibule of the vagina and its glands, and the opening of the urethra and of the vagina
any structural anomaly of the small, erectile body located at the anterior end of the vulva
flattened or spread out clitoris

persistence of an early embryonic state in which the urinary, genital, and gastrointestinal tracts remain confluent and communicate with the exterior through a single perineal opening; due to failure of the urogenital septum to divide the embryonic cloaca into rectal and urogenital portions

definition.value: Note that the term "urogenital sinus" may refer to the primitive urogenital sinus present as a transient developmental structure in most mammals or it may refer to a condition in which an unseptated cloaca persists in animals longer than normal.

value.value: congenital absence of an anal opening due to the persistence of the epithelial plug (persistence of the anal membrane) or to complete absence of the anal canal
greater number of the cells that transport oxygen, red blood cells, per unit
greater number of progenitor cells that form the B cell component of the immune system
greater number of cells in the B lymphocyte lineage that undergo D-J rearrangement of the immunoglobulin heavy chain
greater number of the cells in the B lymphocyte lineage that undergo V-DJ rearrangement of the immunoglobulin heavy chain
greater numbers of progenitors of the erythrocyte lineage
amount and distribution of yellow pigment (phaeomelanin) relative to black or brown pigment (eumelanin) is maximally increased in agouti hair

any functional anomaly in the impulse-conducting system composed of modified cardiac muscle and having the power of spontaneous rhythmicity and conduction more highly developed than the rest of the heart
missing the bony ring at the ear canal to which the tympanic membrane is attached
failure of the fetal connection between the aorta and pulmonary artery to close after birth
the luminal space of one or both of the upper chambers of the heart is increased in volume or area, usually with an increase of contained fluid
formation of fibrous tissue within the heart often resulting from inflammation or injury
congenital absence of one or both auricles of the ears
increased average size of the crystalline calciferous particles adhering to the otolithic membrane
reduced average number of the crystalline calciferous particles adhering to the otolithic membrane
the otolithic (otoconial) membrane is abnormally detached from the underlying neuroepithelium

absence of the group of nerve cell bodies that conveys auditory sensation from the organ of Corti to the hindbrain and resides on the cochlear part of the vestibulocochlear nerve (eighth cranial nerve)
absence or agenesis of the spiral-shaped bony canal in the inner ear containing the hair cells that transduce sound
a reduction in cochlear coiling or number of turns; in wild-type mice, the cochlea most commonly exhibits one and three-fourth turns

any structural anomaly of the overlaying membrane of cochlear duct, an extracellular matrix of the inner ear that contacts the stereocilia bundles of specialized sensory hair cells; sound induces movement of these hair cells relative to the tectorial membrane, deflects the stereocilia, and leads to fluctuations in hair cell membrane potential, transducing sound into electrical signals
tectorial membrane is abnormally detached from the cochlear epithelium or spiral limbus
complete absence of the triangular, fluid-filled space normally found between the inner and outer rows of supporting pillar cells in the organ of Corti
abnormal differentiation of the supporting cells that form the inner and outer walls of the tunnel in the organ of Corti
early average time for the first postnatal eye opening

definition.value: In mouse, eyelids normally fuse about 5 days prior to birth and reopen about 19 days later.

value.value: any structural anomaly of the musculomembranous fold that partly separates the mouth and pharynx, located behind the hard palate in the adult

abnormal length of the terminal repetitive DNA section of a chromosome which is involved in chromosomal replication and senescence, and which protects the end of the chromosome from deterioration; normal length is a few hundred base pairs

altered ability of blood leukocytes to move within or between different tissues and organs of the body by binding to high endothelial venules (HEV), then tethering and rolling along the luminal aspects of HEV
reduced or absent ability of muscle to lengthen following contractions
difficulty in swallowing food or liquid
any structural anomaly of the nonstriated, involuntary muscle tissue lining the esophagus
aberrant formation of the part of the digestive canal through which food passes from the pharynx to the stomach
absence of the lateral long bony tube of the labyrinth that is involved in the sense of balance
